Correct — the current Python uses plain ssh, so it does not handle password prompts or your “Do you agree?” prompt.

Best fix: keep your Expect login wrapper and have the PyQt GUI launch that wrapper.

For the remote monitor button, make a script like this:

#!/usr/bin/expect -f
set timeout 60
set user "YOUR_USER"
set host "YOUR_HOST"
set pass "YOUR_PASSWORD"
set remote_script "/path/on/remote/start_remote.sh"
spawn ssh -tt -o StrictHostKeyChecking=accept-new $user@$host "bash -lc '$remote_script'"
expect {
    -re ".+" {
        set buf $expect_out(buffer)
        if {[string match -nocase "*password:*" $buf]} {
            send -- "$pass\r"
        }
        if {[string match -nocase "*Do you agree*" $buf]} {
            send -- "y\r"
        }
        exp_continue
    }
    timeout { exit 1 }
    eof { exit }
}

Save it as:

remote_monitor_expect.exp

Then:

chmod +x remote_monitor_expect.exp

Now in your PyQt command line, set the remote script to the local Expect wrapper, and make the GUI run it locally instead of wrapping it in ssh.

That means change the remote HostRow from:

remote_host=args.remote_host,

to:

remote_host=None,

for the CLI panel only:

remote_row = HostRow(
    side_title="Laptop",
    side_info=remote_info,
    image_path=args.laptop_image,
    cli_title="LIVE CLI OUTPUT 2",
    cli_subtitle=f"Remote host: {args.remote_host}",
    cli_button_text="Run Remote Script",
    cli_command=args.remote_script,
    file_title="LIVE FILE UPDATE 2",
    file_subtitle="Remote output directories",
    watch_dirs=[
        ("Data", args.remote_watch_dir_1),
        ("Meta", args.remote_watch_dir_2),
        ("Logs", args.remote_watch_dir_3),
    ],
    remote_host=None,
)

Then run the dashboard like:

python3 rf_site_dashboard.py \
  --remote-script "/home/you/scripts/remote_monitor_expect.exp"

Important: the file update boxes only watch local folders. So for remote files, your remote script needs to copy files back to local folders, or you need a separate scp/rsync wrapper that pulls them down.
